<script>
export default {
  name: 'module',
  data() {
    return {moduleName: 'Materials and Sustainable Processes',
year: 'Academic Year 2022',
credit: '20.00',
level: '2',
targetStudents: 'Available to students studying BEng (Hons), Chemical &amp; Environmental Engineering',
offeringSchool: 'Department of Chemical and Environmental Engineeri',
taughtSemesters: 'Spring China',
requisites: 'N/A',
additionalRequirements: 'N/A',
staffName: 'Dr Svenja Hanson',
generalFurtherActivityDetail: '<br>',
educationAims: '<div class="PSLONGEDITBOX" id="UN_PAM_CRSE_DTL_UN_AIMS$0" style="word-wrap: break-word;"><br><p>To expose students to a range of commonly used engineering materials and their properties, and encourage them to develop skills in selecting engineering materials, considering also their end of life <br>To ensure that students understand the main principles of waste management and resource recovery,  and can assess the sustainability implications of waste treatment techniques and technologies, selecting and applying quantitative methods to waste management problems.</p></div>',
learningOutcome: '<div class="PSLONGEDITBOX" id="UN_QAA_CRSE_OUT_UN_LEARN_OUTCOME$0" style="word-wrap: break-word;"><br><p>A1.2.2 Have a knowledge and understanding of basic mathematical models relevant to chemical engineering.</p><ul> <li>Students must use relevant equations to calculate mechanical stresses, corrosion rates and heat transfer rates in materials of construction</li> <li>Assessed by combination of coursework &amp; final written examination.</li></ul><p>A2.1.4 Gain an understanding of the broad range of applications of the principles and develop the ability to analyse, model quantitatively and synthesise at the appropriate scale. The applications should include: Different types of process, including continuous and batch; chemical processes and bioprocesses.</p><p>Process selection and bioprocesses are considered in this module.</p><ul> <li>Assessed by final written examination</li></ul><p>A2.6.0.1 Understand the inherent nature of safety and loss prevention, and the principal hazard sources in chemical and related processes – including flammability, explosivity and toxicity (including biological hazards).</p><ul> <li>Students learn how to select the correct materials of construction to prevent or minimise mechanical failure and corrosion</li> <li>Assessed by combination of coursework &amp; final written examination.</li></ul><p>A2.6.0.2 Understand the principles of risk assessment and of safety management, and be able to apply techniques for the assessment and abatement of process and product hazards.</p><ul> <li>Awareness of the UK risk assessment framework and how to apply conceptual models to waste management.</li> <li>Assessed by final written examination</li></ul><p>A2.6.0.5 Have knowledge of the local legislative framework and how it is applied to the management of safety, health and environment in practice and in the workplace, from the perspectives of all involved, including operators, designers, contractors, researchers, visitors and the public.</p><ul> <li>Knowledge of the Waste Framework Directive and other relevant legislation and their application in the classification, handling, reuse and disposal of wastes and materials.</li> <li>Assessed by final written examination</li></ul><p>A2.7.0.1 Understand the principles of sustainability (environmental, social and economic) and be able to apply techniques for analysing, throughout the lifecycle, the interaction of process, product and plant with the environment.</p><ul> <li>Knowledge of the range of waste treatment technologies currently in use in Europe and the ability to select an appropriate process based on a range of social, economic and technical factors over the lifetime of an operation.</li> <li>Assessed by final written examination</li></ul><p>A2.7.0.2 Understand and be able to apply the main methods of minimizing the environmental impact on air, water, land, and integrated eco-systems, including waste minimization at source and ‘end-of-pipe’ methods.</p><ul> <li>Knowledge of the range of waste treatment technologies currently in use in Europe and the ability to select an appropriate process based on a range of social, economic and technical factors.</li> <li>Assessed by final written examination</li></ul><p>A3.2.3 Be able to find and apply, with judgement, information from technical literature and other sources.</p><ul> <li>Students must identify and review appropriate sources for material property data</li> <li>Assessed by combination of coursework &amp; final written examination.</li></ul><p>A3.2.4 Be aware of the importance of codes of practice and industry standards and have some experience in applying them.</p><ul> <li>Students must use relevant industry standards when selecting materials for their components</li> <li>Assessed by combination of coursework &amp; final written examination.</li></ul><p style="margin-left:.25in;"> </p><p>A4.1.3 Encourage students to develop and demonstrate creative and critical powers by requiring choices and decisions to be made in areas of uncertainty</p><ul> <li>Students must make well informed material selection decisions when faced with numerous acceptable options</li> <li>Assessed by combination of coursework &amp; final written examination.</li></ul><p>A6.0.1 Have the ability to handle uncertainty and complexity</p><ul> <li>Awareness that waste management inherently has a lot of uncertainty due to variability in feedstocks and natural environments, and this must be considered in decision making.</li></ul><p><span style="font-family:verdana,sans-serif;"><span style="font-size:10.0pt;">Assessed by final written examination</span></span></p></div>',
summaryOfContent: '<div class="PSLONGEDITBOX" id="UN_PAM_CRSE_DTL_UN_SUMMARY_CONTENT$0" style="word-wrap: break-word;"><br><p>This module looks into the life cycle of materials, considering their selection and their end of life.  At the process input end it provides an introduction to the properties of engineering materials including topics such as, mechanical properties, elasticity, creep, fatigue and fracture. The module also provides insight into elements of material selection procedures for chemical, mechanical and structural design. It ehn moves to the end of life and introduces students to a range of knowledge and skills applicable to the management of waste. The development of legislation will be covered as well as current waste treatment techniques and technologies including biological methods (composting, anaerobic digestion), thermal methods (energy from waste, gasification, pyrolysis), mechanical biological treatment and landfilling. Techniques and approaches for the recovery and recycling of waste products will be a core component. Successful waste/resource recovery schemes are highlighted as case studies.</p></div>',
